WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.120
I think I had been concerned as early as March 2020 that there were I'd say generally underappreciated

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:19.920
risks associated with attending even medium to small events. Cases were spreading, it was hard

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:23.600
to figure out how many cases there really were. There were all these questions of whether or not

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:27.680
the case were being documented and we're fairly certain they were under ascertained, under

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:34.480
documented. And we wanted to translate that in some way to communicate that out to the world.

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:42.160
So one of the big things that we focus on is creating like interactive interfaces around not

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:47.520
just like bioinformatics tools but also say public health related things. So in our Shiny is really

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:52.639
a great tool for this. I put out a tweet which tried to highlight this relationship between

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:58.560
how big an event was, how many people might be infected, whether there was uncertainty,

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:02.080
and highlighting the risk that one or more individuals in a group of that size at that

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:07.760
moment might be infected, leading to obviously potential risks for spread. This went in its

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:12.639
own way viral and spread very rapidly. I think people started to realize that this was a

00:01:13.279 --> 00:01:17.599
compelling communication tool. Think about who your audience is going to be

00:01:18.559 --> 00:01:25.120
absolutely and don't think about like oh I would find this cool so other people would find it

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:33.279
cool too. So we had to take all of those different individual data sets and some of those listed

00:01:33.279 --> 00:01:38.720
cumulative cases, some of them listed daily cases, and we had to make sure that was all formatted

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:45.599
correctly. The balancing between how straight the straightforwardness of our app and the number

00:01:45.599 --> 00:01:51.519
of information or selectable variables in our app was one of the most discussed topics in our

00:01:51.519 --> 00:01:58.639
discussions I think. We just want to focus on what is the most important thing and to present

00:01:58.639 --> 00:02:04.559
information for the users. We don't need something like very big, very fancy, but like something very

00:02:04.559 --> 00:02:13.039
essential. I mean theoretically it would be better if we have more options but we need to limit that

00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:19.679
number of options to make the speed or the usability of the app good enough. So I think we

00:02:19.679 --> 00:02:29.520
ended up having keeping only two user variables. One was the size of the events and one other was

00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:36.399
the assertive bias which can vary across the different locales. We originally were thinking

00:02:36.399 --> 00:02:44.399
about data applied to Georgia as the state and at that same kind of time this

00:02:45.360 --> 00:02:51.119
mapping project was taking off. We launched a state-level thing in May without the visualization

00:02:51.679 --> 00:02:57.039
and it's really the visualization that we worked so hard on with Clio and Solha that when that was

00:02:57.039 --> 00:03:02.880
released in that day it was very clear. I had some expectation it would spread but this was

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:07.520
it went much faster. That's in part because it started to spread on Facebook

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:13.759
and Twitter and Instagram and started to go through social media sites. And that really was this kind

00:03:13.759 --> 00:03:22.479
of stepping stone into this project where we then applied that concept to other countries

00:03:22.479 --> 00:03:29.839
in Europe. This particular metric I think is something that people can really get grips on

00:03:29.839 --> 00:03:36.320
and understand a lot more easily than some of the other ones like cases per 100,000 people. I mean

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:45.119
I don't even know a bigger group 100,000 people how much space they would take up but it's very

00:03:45.119 --> 00:03:49.839
hard to visualize and think about. To communicate risk at a personal level right that people get

00:03:49.839 --> 00:03:54.240
what it means to be at a restaurant with 50 people. They're not sure what to always do with

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:59.520
a positivity rate or case rates that are cumulative because that's not necessarily

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:05.600
the relevant risk at that moment. Making sure that as developers you have a question in mind

00:04:06.399 --> 00:04:12.160
and I think that requires taking a bit of an empathetic perspective with respect to your

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:17.920
potential users. It wasn't meant to be complicated it was meant to be accessible and trying to take

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:22.160
simple quantitative principles in the midst of pandemic and letting them

00:04:22.880 --> 00:04:26.160
be utilized in this really this kind of public accessible format.

00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:30.480
you

